<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="trans-alt-inline" xml:lang="en">
    <head>Alternative readings: inline encoding and display</head>
    <p> Where there are two or more possible readings or interpretations of a string of text, an
        editor may choose to present all options to the reader for full transparency. In EpiDoc,
        these readings are encoded using the <gi>app</gi> element with <gi>lem</gi> (the preferred
        reading; optional) and one or more <gi>rdg</gi>s (all other reading). On a project level,
        the editor(s) might decide to display this variety of readings in a separate apparatus
        criticus or in the body of the text. Here follow examples of the latter.</p>
    <p>
        <specList>
            <specDesc key="app"/>
            <specDesc key="lem"/>
            <specDesc key="rdg"/>
        </specList>
    </p>

    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" corresp="https://iospe.kcl.ac.uk/5.1.html">
        <app type="alternative">
            <lem>
                <num value="13">ιγ</num>
            </lem>
            <rdg>
                <num value="13">ι<surplus>γ</surplus></num>
            </rdg>
        </app>
    </egXML>
    <note>displayed in the edition as: ιγ´ resp. ι{γ}´.</note> 
    
    <p>A second example, with two expansions of
        abbreviation:</p>

    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples" corresp="https://sigidoc.raketadesign.com/en/seals/TM_16.html">
        <app type="alternative">
            <lem>
                <expan><abbr>χ</abbr><ex>α</ex><abbr>ρτελ</abbr><ex>αρίῳ</ex></expan>
            </lem>
            <rdg>
                <expan><ex>χρυσο</ex><abbr>τελ</abbr><ex>ῇ</ex></expan>
            </rdg>
        </app>
    </egXML>
    <note>displayed in the edition as: χ(α)ρτελ(αρίῳ) <hi rend="italic">vel</hi>
        (χρυσο)τελ(ῇ).</note>

    <p>The <gi>app</gi> element should have a <att>type</att> attribute of "alternative".</p>

